description: From Middle English ful, from Old English full (“full”), from Proto-West Germanic *full, from Proto-Germanic *fullaz (“full”), from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁nós (“full”).

Germanic cognates include West Frisian fol, Low German vull, Dutch vol, German voll, Danish fuld, and Norwegian and Swedish full (the latter three via Old Norse). Proto-Indo-European cognates include English plenty (via Latin, compare plēnus), Welsh llawn, Russian по́лный (pólnyj), Lithuanian pilnas, Persian پر‎ (por), Sanskrit पूर्ण (pūrṇa). See also fele.

entries.meaning: Containing the maximum possible amount that can fit in the space available.
examples: The jugs were full to the point of overflowing.

entries.meaning: Complete; with nothing omitted.
examples: Our book gives full treatment to the subject of angling.

entries.meaning: Total, entire.
examples: She had tattoos the full length of her arms.   He was prosecuted to the full extent of the law.

entries.meaning: Completely empowered, authorized or qualified (in some role); not limited.
examples: full member
full officer

entries.meaning: (informal) Having eaten to satisfaction, having a "full" stomach; replete.
examples: "I'm full," he said, pushing back from the table.

entries.meaning: (informal, with of) Replete, abounding with.
examples: This movie doesn't make sense; it's full of plot holes.
I prefer my pizzas full of toppings.

entries.meaning: (of physical features) Plump, round.
examples: full lips; a full face; a full figure

entries.meaning: (of the moon) Having its entire face illuminated.
examples: For on those evenings, when the moon is full and bright and clear, mothers and fathers in Siam tell their children to look up at the moon and then ask them what they see there.

entries.meaning: (of garments) Of a size that is ample, wide, or having ample folds or pleats to be comfortable.
examples: a full pleated skirt; She needed her full clothing during her pregnancy.

entries.meaning: Having depth and body; rich.
examples: a full singing voice

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Having the mind filled with ideas; stocked with knowledge; stored with information.
Having the attention, thoughts, etc., absorbed in any matter, and the feelings more or less excited by it.
examples: She's full of her latest project.

entries.meaning: Filled with emotions.
examples: The heart is so full that a drop overfills it.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Impregnated; made pregnant.
(poker, postnominal) Said of the three cards of the same rank in a full house.
examples: nines full of aces (three nines and two aces)
I'll beat him with my kings full! (three kings and two unspecified cards of the same rank)

entries.meaning: (chiefly Australia) Drunk, intoxicated.
examples: Mr. Coniff: That is the only evidence you gave of his being intoxicated, that his hat was on the side?  […]  Mr. Coniff: That is the only indication you gave the committee when you were asked if the judge was full, that his hat was on the side of his head; is that right?

entries.meaning: (archaic) Fully; quite; very; thoroughly; completely; exactly; entirely.
examples: […]  full in the centre of the sacred wood

description: From Middle English fulle, fylle, fille, from Old English fyllu, fyllo (“fullness, fill, plenty”), from Proto-Germanic *fullį̄, *fulnō (“fullness, filling, overflow”), from Proto-Indo-European *plūno-, *plno- (“full”), from *pelh₁-, *pleh₁- (“to fill; full”). Cognate with German Fülle (“fullness, fill”), Icelandic fylli (“fulness, fill”). More at fill.

entries.meaning: Utmost measure or extent; highest state or degree; the state, position, or moment of fullness; fill.
examples: I was fed to the full.

entries.meaning: (of the moon) The phase of the moon when its entire face is illuminated, full moon.
examples: It is like, that the brain of man waxeth moister and fuller upon the full of the moon: [...]

entries.meaning: (freestyle skiing) An aerialist maneuver consisting of a backflip in conjunction and simultaneous with a complete twist.

verbs.description: full (third-person singular simple present fulls, present participle fulling, simple past and past participle fulled)

entries.meaning: (of the moon) To become full or wholly illuminated.
examples: The September moon fulls on the 20th at 24 minutes past midnight, and is called the harvest moon.

description: From Middle English fullen (“to baptise”), fulwen, from Old English fullian, fulwian (“to baptise”), from full- + *wīhan (later *wēon). Compare Old English fulluht, fulwiht (“baptism”).

entries.meaning: (transitive) To baptise.

description: From Middle English fullen (“to full”), from Middle French fouler, from Old French foler, fouler (“to tread, to stamp, to full”), from Medieval Latin fullare, from Latin fullo (“a fuller”).

examples: Synonyms: walk, waulk
